# Baseline System Hardening

## Project Objective
To take a default, out-of-the-box operating system (Windows or Linux) and configure it according to industry security standards.
You will disable unnecessary services, configure the local firewall, and enforce strict user policies to protect the machine from unauthorized access.

## What you will need
Hypervisor: VMware Workstation Pro
Operating System: Windows 10 or Kali Linux
A Security Framework: The CIS Benchmarks

## FOLLOW THE SEQUENCE
Phase 1: Deployment & Baselining
         -Install a fresh copy of your chosen OS on a virtual machine.
         -Before changing anything, document the "baseline."
         -Open your command line and check what network ports are listening by default (using netstat -ano in Windows)
         -Look at the default password requirements.

Phase 2: Identity & Access Hardening
         This is where you lock down who can access the system.
         -Open the Local Security Policy tool (secpol.msc in Windows).
         -Enforce a password policy: Require at least 14 characters, complexity (numbers/symbols),
           and set an account lockout policy (e.g., the account locks for 30 minutes after 5 failed login attempts.
         -Disable default accounts like the built-in "Guest" or "Administrator" accounts.

Phase 3: Service & Network Hardening
         Lock down how the system communicates.
         -Configure the local firewall to block all incoming traffic by default, only allowing exactly what is neccessary.
         -Open the Services menu (services.msc) and disable legacy or risky services.
          A classic example in Windows is disabling SMBv1, which is a massive security risk,
          or disabling the Print Spooler if the machine isn't connected to a printer.

Phase 4: Automation
        Instead of clicking through menus to make these 50+ changes manually, write a PowerShell
        script (for Windows) or a Bash script (for Linux) that changes the registry keys and firewall rules for you. This shows massive value to employers.
